"Twenty Squares: An Ancient Board Game" by Anne Dunn-Vaturi

Twenty Squares: An Ancient Board Game
December 9, 2014 
Anne Dunn-Vaturi, Research Associate, Provenance, Department of Ancient Near Eastern Art

Image: Game box with chariot hunt, ca. 1250�1100 B.C. Enkomi, Cyprus. The Trustees of the British Museum

Board games were popular entertainments in the ancient Near East. So what games did the Assyrians and the Phoenicians like to play? Part of the answer is in the very first room of the exhibition Assyria to Iberia at the Dawn of the Classical Age,�on an ivory box from Enkomi. This unique object has a grid with twenty playing squares incised on its upper surface. Although no accessories were found with this box, we can deduce from other archaeological assemblages and pictorial representations what kind of pieces and dice were required.

Image: Double-sided game box with playing pieces and a pair of knucklebones. Thebes, Egypt. ca. 1635�1458 B.C. The Metropolitan Museum of Art, New York, Rogers Fund, 1916 (16.10.475a). This work is on permanent display in Gallery 114.

It is generally assumed that the two players started on each of the opposite sides of the board, as shown in the drawing below. They then moved their pieces down the central aisle toward the final field and off the board to win the game. Every fourth square is marked with a rosette or other symbol or inscription. These special squares seem to have functioned as lucky fields, be it that a piece was safe from being captured or that the player was given another throw. We know from liver-shaped game boards that divination was sometimes even performed on such surfaces. The use of dice�instruments of chance�placed the final outcome in the hands of Fate or Divine Will.

The game of twenty squares in the second and first millennia B.C. and the route of play. After I. Finkel, "On the Rules for the Royal Game of Ur," Ancient Board Games in Perspective, British Museum Press, 2007 (fig. 3.5)

Additional videos about rules and game play for twenty squares are available on the website of the Harvard Semitic Museum: http://semiticmuseum.fas.harvard.edu/games

"Twenty Squares: An Ancient Board Game" by Anne Dunn-Vaturi

The game box from Enkomi represents the westernmost example of the game of twenty squares. This game, distributed from Iran to the Levant, was certainly one of the most popular board games in the ancient Near East from the mid-third to the mid-first millennium B.C. It is also known as the Royal Game of Ur, since the famous Sumerian boards from Ur in southern Mesopotamia (modern Iraq) were early versions of this game.

Image: Royal Game of Ur with gaming pieces and tetrahedrons, ca. 2600 B.C. The Trustees of the British Museum. This example was among the highlights of the exhibition Art of the First Cities: The Third Millennium B.C. from the Mediterranean to the Indus, organized by the Metropolitan Museum of Art in 2003.

Board games are found in many forms�from graffiti scratched on bricks to elaborately designed boxes�showing that they were popular with players of all social classes. Prestigious game boxes were among the luxury goods that circulated between the palatial societies of the Eastern Mediterranean. Most of the archaeological evidence of gaming material comes from funerary contexts, as grave offerings are often better preserved than other objects. Many games have vanished because their boards were made from perishable material, such as textile, leather, and wood, or simply drawn on the ground.

In Egypt and the Levant, grids for the game of twenty squares were combined with those for the famous Egyptian game of senet, meaning "passing," and strongly connected with the journey to the afterlife. The idea of having two games on the opposite sides of reversible boxes, with a drawer to keep the playing pieces and dice, is certainly one of the most brilliant in the history of board game design. It has been suggested that the box from Enkomi had a senet track on its underside, which had disintegrated by the time the box was excavated.

Ivory or bone games were still being produced in the early first millennium B.C. in the Levant. In fact, a complete playing surface with the special squares signaled by rosettes, like the Enkomi track, was recently discovered at Gezer in Israel.

Image: Ivory game board, 10th�9th century B.C. Tel Gezer. Excavations co-directed by Steven Ortiz of the Tandy Institute for Archaeology and Samuel Wolff of the Israel Antiquities Authority. Photograph by Annie Wegman

No doubt, some of the ivory plaques discovered at Nimrud may have once adorned game boards. Thanks to stone examples, we know that board games such as the game of twenty squares and the game of fifty-eight holes were part of the entertainment at the Assyrian court. Moreover, rough tracks scratched on the base of stone sculptures revealed that the game of twenty squares was played by some guards on duty in Sargon's palace at Khorsabad, about 705 B.C.

"Twenty Squares: An Ancient Board Game" by Anne Dunn-Vaturi

Beautifully carved with a chariot hunt and animal scenes, the side panels of the Enkomi box illustrate a long tradition of decorated board games. Combat scenes and animals in confrontation are often depicted on gaming boxes as a metaphor for the contest between the players.

Image: Chariot scene on the reverse of a game of twenty squares. Tell Halaf, Syria, early first millenium B.C. After D. van Buren, "A Gaming-board from Tall Halaf," Iraq 1, 1937 (fig. 1). This stone game board, was recently identified during the restoration project of the Tell Halaf Museum collection.

The rosette, a benevolent motif, is omnipresent in the ancient Near East, as is demonstrated in Assyria to Iberia at the Dawn of the Classical Age. It is the traditional emblem of Inanna/Ishtar, the most important female deity in ancient Mesopotamia, and occasionally replaced the star as her symbol in her astral aspect of the planet Venus (the morning and evening star). As goddess of war, Inanna/Ishtar was well suited to oversee the metaphoric battle of a game, so it makes sense that the rosette was an essential symbol on game boards as early as the third millennium B.C. In addition to being placed in special squares to indicate certain privileges, the rosettes are also featured on the outside of the playing surface, on the side of the board, or on its reverse. 

Image: Detail of the decorated side of a game of twenty squares, Balawat (Iraq). 9th�8th century B.C. Mus�e du Louvre. Photograph by Sarah Graff

Image: Drawing of a game of 58 holes and its reverse. Said to be from Luristan, early 1st millenium B.C. Mus�e du Louvre. Drawing by Caroline Florimont

"Deciphering the world's oldest rule book with  Irving Finkel." The British Museum (Youtube)

My name is Dr. Irving Finkel and I'm a curator at the British Museum in London and welcome to my corner! I'm a curator, I've already admitted it but I have a slightly strange aspect to my curatorship because I've always wanted to be a curator in this very building. Because when I was about 9 years old already I'd decided that that's what I wanted to do and I've been very fortunate because through a whole bewildering series of circumstances that's what happened to me. I ended up becoming one and I've been one for ages and I'm going to be here for another 500 years! So I work in this department where we have all sorts of treasures from antiquity, rescued from the soil and looked after forever and among their treasures, perhaps the most significant, are the cuneiform inscriptions written on bits of clay which came out of the ground in Iraq excavated mostly in the 19th century and brought to the British Museum where they've been looked after ever since. And we have about 130,000 of them.

"Deciphering the world's oldest rule book with  Irving Finkel." The British Museum (Youtube)

They cover 3000 years of time from the beginning of writing, down to the time of Jesus and slightly later into the first century AD. Now it's impossible for anyone in the world to imagine what it is like firstly to get a job in the one building in the world you wanted to get a job in because it is the most important building in the universe. And secondly to get the keys to the cupboards because in my department like all the other departments the collections are incalculably wonderfuly and incalculably huge and the material is just fantastic. It makes a kid in a toy shop or chocolate shop a trivial matter because you can open chest after chest of treasure and examine what's inside And when it came to inscriptions there were as I said 130,000 of them and I've looked at them all at least 3 times and they are full of marvellous, marvellous things.

"Deciphering the world's oldest rule book with  Irving Finkel." The British Museum (Youtube)

One of my favourite ones is something quite extraordinary because it was written in the second century BC a very late tablet in Babylonian terms, which has on it the following marvelous thing. It tells you how to play the national board game of Ancient Mesopotamia. I found this after about 2 years and I worked on it because I've always liked reading things which are difficult and this tablet was very difficult and I worked on it and worked on it and worked on it and I knew it was a game and I knew it was rules. But the problem was if you've got the rules and you don't know which board it is what do you do with the rules? So I tried it out on all the ancient games that we knew the ones from Egypt, the ones from Mesopotamia and when it came to the game of twenty squares it fitted perfectly. This is not the real board, it is a very good replica. It's a kind of photograph of the original so it gives you a really good idea. So, one player will come in from this corner go down this edge, up the middle and then turn round and off in that direction. Whereas his opponent will come down this side go up the middle here and then off that side.

"Deciphering the world's oldest rule book with  Irving Finkel." The British Museum (Youtube)

Come over here and have a look because this is the real board, the original board from about 2,500 BC and next to it you can see the round black pieces and the round white pieces for the two sides of players. There are two kinds of dice that they could use in order to generate the scores. And over here we have this clay tablet not quite complete, a little bit broken, which has on it the rules which allow us to see how this game was played in ancient times and we can see that it was a good and exciting race game. So it's really quite true that I've been interested in this game almost all my life because I made this when I was about nine when I first got interested. I copied a photograph of the original thing in a book as best I could. Sawed this out without cutting off a finger, and painted all these things on the front to try to have a good working example of this board to experiment with and I have to say that I feel quite guilty now when I think about it because I made my poor sister Angela play this game endlessly with me to see if we could work out how the rules
worked on the basis of the ones which people thought applied before we found the tablet in The British Museum which meant that we really knew how the game was played. So, this goes back almost as long as I do and I'm rather proud of it.

"Deciphering the world's oldest rule book with  Irving Finkel." The British Museum (Youtube)

So wherever you go in the world, you will find someone who can play chess or probably backgammon and that's how this game was - and that tablet is only the beginning of a long story and I've decided to write a big fat book all about these ancient games because there's something to be said about the ones from Egypt and the ones from the other parts of the world, and to put them altogether and I had this idea, when you write about things which are inert and dead, if you write about them when they're inert and dead then they remain inert and dead but if you imagine people playing them, for example in a bar, you might imagine in Syria there are a couple of local merchant s and some weird bloke from Afghanistan and some weird bloke from Iraq and they're all sitting back drinking and someone starts playing and they start saying 'oh what's all that?' - they don't know how to say 'what's all that?' but they look over their shoulder and then after a while they have a go. The next minute they're all betting and the next minute they're all having a fight, two
of them in hospital.

"Deciphering the world's oldest rule book with  Irving Finkel." The British Museum (Youtube)

It's a good healthy activity, and I try to imagine all these games in their sort of function. When you start to look at it like that, it's a kind of volcanic matter, which is... you have a small kernel of idea and it explodes into something where the whole history of the world seems to be summed up in it. One piece of clay is full of words, it's full of grammatical problems, it's full of how to read it but when you've done this, when you've translated it when you've got everything under control from a professional point of view, THEN is the time to try and understand what it meant. I'm kind of obsessed with the idea of doing this with this material, so that when people are here they don't say 'Oh well this is a really boring place' or 'Why do we have to look at all this stuff?' or 'My legs ache' or 'Do we have to go and look at that?' or 'Do we really have to be here any longer?' - that they should never want to go home, that they should see things with their mouths getting wider and wider and wider, and they only go home when eventually they are herded out of the building by apologetic warders.
